President Barack Obama released a statement on the situation in Egypt, expressing concern that the transition of authority in the country may not be immediate, meaningful, or sufficient. He emphasized the importance of the Egyptian government clearly communicating its commitment to a genuine transition to democracy. Obama called for a credible and concrete plan towards democracy, including the lifting of the emergency law, meaningful negotiations with the opposition, and a clear roadmap to free and fair elections. He urged the government to explain the changes that have been made and to ensure the universal rights of the Egyptian people are respected. Obama also emphasized the need for restraint and non-violence from all parties involved. He praised the peaceful protesters for representing the greatness of the Egyptian people, and expressed support for the aspirations of the Egyptian youth. Obama reassured the Egyptian people that they will continue to have a friend in the United States.